<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1>Pythagorean Theorem</h1>=20


<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/pythagoras.jpg" alt=3D"pythagoras" height=3D"200" width=3D"140"><br>
<i>Pythagoras</i></p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>Over 2000 years ago there was an amazing discovery about triangles:</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"large center"><i> When a triangle has a right angle (90=C2=B0) =
...</i></p>=20
<p class=3D"large center"><i>... and squares are made on each of the three =
sides, ...</i></p>=20

<iframe width=3D"100%" height=3D"335px" scrolling=3D"no" title=3D"JavaScrip=
t Animation" style=3D"display: block; margin: auto; border: none; backgroun=
d-color: transparent; overflow: hidden; transition: 0.6s ease-in-out; max-w=
idth: 100%;"></iframe><div class=3D"script" style=3D"height: 330px; display=
: none;"> geometry/images/pyth1.js</div>
<p class=3D"large"><i>... then the biggest square has the <b>exact same are=
a</b> as the other two squares put together! (press Go)</i>.</p><br>

<div class=3D"clear"></div>
<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/pythagoras-abc.svg" alt=3D"Pythagoras" height=3D"242" width=3D"221"></p>=
=20
<p>It is the "Pythagorean Theorem" and can be written in one short equation=
:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c<sup=
>2</sup></p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
pythagoras-squares.svg" alt=3D"pythagoras a^2+b^2=3Dc^2" height=3D"109" wid=
th=3D"375"></p>=20
<p>Note:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>c</b> is the <span class=3D"large"> <b>longest side</b> of the tria=
ngle</span></li>=20
	<li><b>a</b> and <b>b</b> are the other two sides</li>=20
</ul>=20


<h2>Definition</h2>=20

<p>The longest side of the triangle is called the "hypotenuse", so the form=
al definition is:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center large">In a right angled triangle:<br>
the square of the hypotenuse is equal to<br>
the sum of the squares of the other two sides.</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Sure ... ?</h2>=20

<p>Let's see if it really works using an example.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: A <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/triangle-3-4=
-5.html">"3, 4, 5" triangle</a> has a right angle in it.</h3>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/triangle-3-4-=
5-pyth.svg" alt=3D"triangle 3 4 5" height=3D"229" width=3D"209"></td>
			<td><br>


	<p>Let's check if the areas <b>are</b> the same:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">3<sup>2</sup> + 4<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 5<su=
p>2</sup></p>=20
	<p>Calculating this becomes:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">9 + 16 <em>=3D</em> 25</p>=20
	<p><i>It works ... like Magic!</i></p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
triangle-3-4-5-leg.jpg" alt=3D"triangle 3 4 5 lego" height=3D"216" width=3D=
"200"></p>=20


<h2>Why Is This Useful?</h2>=20

<p class=3D"large">When we know <b>two side lengths</b> of a right triangle=
 we can find the <b>third side length</b>.</p>=20


<h2>How Do I Use it?</h2>=20

<p>Write it down as an equation:</p>=20
<div class=3D"clear">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/triangle-abc.=
svg" alt=3D"abc triangle" height=3D"109" width=3D"189"></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"large">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c<s=
up>2</sup></span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"center"></div>
<p><br>
Then we use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/index.html">algeb=
ra</a> to find any missing value, as in these examples:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Solve this triangle</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/triangle-5-12-c.svg" alt=3D"right angled triangle 5 12 c" height=3D"87" wi=
dth=3D"176"></p>=20
	<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">Start with:</span><span class=3D"rt=
">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup></span><span clas=
s=3D"lt">Put in what we know:</span><span class=3D"rt">5<sup>2</sup> + 12<s=
up>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"lt">Calculate sq=
uares:</span><span class=3D"rt">25 + 144 <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup></span><=
span class=3D"lt">25+144=3D169:</span><span class=3D"rt">169 <em>=3D</em> c=
<sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"lt">Swap sides:</span><span class=3D"rt">=
c<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 169</span><span class=3D"lt">Square root of both=
 sides:</span><span class=3D"rt">c <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A169 </span><span c=
lass=3D"lt">Calculate:</span><span class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"large"><b>c =
<em>=3D</em> 13</b> </span></span></div>
</div>=20

<p>Read about <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/square-root.html">Squar=
es and Square Roots</a> to discover why <span class=3D"larger">=E2=88=9A</s=
pan>169 <em>=3D</em> 13</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Solve this triangle.</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/triangle-9-b-15.svg" alt=3D"right angled triangle 9 b 15" height=3D"114" w=
idth=3D"142"></p>=20
	<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">Start with:</span><span class=3D"rt=
">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup></span><span clas=
s=3D"lt">Put in what we know:</span><span class=3D"rt">9<sup>2</sup> + b<su=
p>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 15<sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"lt">Calculate sq=
uares:</span><span class=3D"rt">81 + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 225 </span>=
<span class=3D"lt">Take 81 from both sides: </span><span class=3D"rt">81 =
=E2=88=92 81 + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 225 =E2=88=92 81</span><span clas=
s=3D"lt">Calculate: </span><span class=3D"rt">b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 14=
4</span><span class=3D"lt">Square root of both sides:</span><span class=3D"=
rt">b <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A144 </span><span class=3D"lt">Calculate:</span>=
<span class=3D"rt"><b>b <em>=3D</em> 12</b> </span></div>

</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is the diagonal distance across a square of size 1?</h3>=
=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/unit-squ=
are-diagonal.gif" alt=3D"Unit Square Diagonal" height=3D"141" width=3D"128"=
></p>=20
	<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">Start with:</span><span class=3D"rt=
">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup></span><span clas=
s=3D"lt">Put in what we know:</span><span class=3D"rt">1<sup>2</sup> + 1<su=
p>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"lt">Calculate squ=
ares:</span><span class=3D"rt">1 + 1 <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup></span><span=
 class=3D"lt">1+1=3D2: </span><span class=3D"rt">2 <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</su=
p></span><span class=3D"lt">Swap sides: </span><span class=3D"rt">c<sup>2</=
sup> <em>=3D</em> 2</span><span class=3D"lt">Square root of both sides:</sp=
an><span class=3D"rt"><b>c <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A2</b></span><span class=3D=
"lt">Which is about:</span><span class=3D"rt"><b>c <em>=3D</em> 1,4142...</=
b></span></div>

</div><br>


<div class=3D"center large">=20
<div class=3D"box"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/t=
riangle-build-diag1.svg" alt=3D"Multiples of 3,4,5" height=3D"141" width=3D=
"307"><br>
There are practical uses!<br>
Read <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/builders-math.html">Bui=
lder's Mathematics</a>.=20
</div>=20

</div>=20


<h2>Is it a Right Angle?</h2>=20

<p>It works the other way around, too: when the three sides of a triangle m=
ake <span class=3D"large nobr">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c=
<sup>2</sup></span>, then the triangle is right angled.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Does this triangle have a Right Angle?</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/triangle-10-24-26.svg" alt=3D"10 24 26 triangle" height=3D"157" width=3D"1=
60"></p>=20
	<p>Does<span class=3D"large"> a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> c=
<sup>2</sup> ?</span></p>=20
	<div class=3D"two">=20
	<div class=3D"lt">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em> 10<sup>2</sup> + 24<sup>2</sup></div>
<div class=3D"lt"></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em> 100 + 576</div>
<div class=3D"lt"></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em><b> 676</b></div>

</div>=20

<div class=3D"two">=20
<div class=3D"lt">c<sup>2</sup></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em> 26<sup>2</sup></div>
<div class=3D"lt"></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em> <b>676</b></div>

</div>=20

<p>Which shows us that <span class=3D"large"> a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup>=
</span> <b>is</b> equal to <span class=3D"large"> c<sup>2</sup></span>, so =
...</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">Yes, it does have a Right Angle!</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Does an 8, 15, 16 triangle have a Right Angle?</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"large"><b>Does 8</b><sup>2</sup> + <b>15</b><sup>2</sup> <em>=
=3D</em> <b>16</b><sup>2 </sup>?</p>=20
	<div class=3D"two">=20
	<div class=3D"lt">8<sup>2</sup> + 15<sup>2</sup></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em> 64 + 225</div>
<div class=3D"lt"></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em> <b>289</b></div>
<div class=3D"lt">16<sup>2 </sup></div>
<div class=3D"rt"><em>=3D</em> <b>256</b></div>
</div>=20

<p class=3D"center">they are not equal</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">So, NO, it does not have a Right Angle</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Does this triangle have a Right Angle?</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/triangle-r3-r5-r8.svg" alt=3D"Triangle with roots" height=3D"151" width=3D=
"103"></p>=20
	<div class=3D"so">Does<span class=3D"large"> a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup>=
 <em>=3D</em> c<sup>2</sup> ?</span></div>
<div class=3D"so">Does (<b>=E2=88=9A</b>3)<sup>2</sup> + (<b>=E2=88=9A</b>5=
)<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> (<b>=E2=88=9A</b>8)<sup>2</sup> ?</div>
<div class=3D"so"><span class=3D"large">Does 3 + 5 <em>=3D</em> 8 ?</span><=
/div>
<p class=3D"center larger">Yes, it does!</p>=20
<p>So this <b>is</b> a right-angled triangle</p>=20
</div>=20



<h2>And You Can Prove The Theorem Yourself !</h2>=20

<p>Get paper pen and scissors, then using the following animation as a guid=
e:</p>=20
<!--
<p class=3D"center"><iframe src=3D"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_87RbSoELW=
8?rel=3D0&amp;showinfo=3D0" allowfullscreen=3D"" title=3D"Pythagorean proof=
" height=3D"203" width=3D"360"></iframe></p> -->=20
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><iframe src=3D"cid:frame-F3CA91CEFBB6CA918=
