""> </iframe></p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Draw a right angled triangle on the paper, leaving plenty of space</li=
>=20
	<li>Draw a square along the hypotenuse (the longest side)</li>=20
	<li>Draw the same sized square on the other side of the hypotenuse</li>=20
	<li>Draw lines as shown on the animation, like this:</li>=20
	<li><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/pythagoras-cutout.png" a=
lt=3D"cut sqaure" height=3D"101" width=3D"102"></li>=20
	<li>Cut out the shapes</li>=20
	<li>Arrange them so that you can prove that the big square has the same ar=
ea as the two squares on the other sides</li>=20
</ul>=20


<h2>Another, Amazingly Simple, Proof</h2>=20

<p>Here is one of the oldest proofs that the square on the long side has th=
e same area as the other squares.</p>=20
<!--
<p class=3D"center"><iframe src=3D"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Zb0thZ6_5G=
